#Load data

# note the use of the here() package and not absolute paths
dataSPOT <- here::here("data","processed_data","smalldta.rds")
dataSPOT2 <- here::here("data","processed_data","feverdta.rds")
# load data. 
# note. processeddta is our main cleaned fata set. Fever data is just those who have fever, 
processeddta <-readRDS(dataSPOT)
feverdta <-readRDS(dataSPOT2)
# take a look at the main data
dplyr::glimpse(processeddta)

End goal:

  • Main continuous outcome of interest = Body temperature
  • Main categorical outcome = Nausea
  • We want to see if the other symptoms are correlated with (predict) those outcomes we looked at in the EDA. The predictors of interest are as follows:
  • Fatigue (y/n)
  • CoughIntensity (none/mild/moderate/severe)
  • ChillsSweats (y/n)
  • SwollenLymphNodes (y/n)
  • Pharyngitis (y/n)
  • Insomnia (y/n)
  • Headache (y/n)
  • SubjectiveFever (y/n)

Model 1. Fitting a linear model to BodyTemp using Chill Sweats the main predictor of interest

# Using the tidymodels package, I am going to set up the linear model
# Set the engine
lm_mod <-  linear_reg() %>% 
  set_engine("lm") 
# Now I am fitting the model
lm_fit <- 
  lm_mod %>% 
  fit(BodyTemp ~ ChillsSweats, data = processeddta)
tidy(lm_fit)
## # A tibble: 2  5
##   term            estimate std.error statistic  p.value
##   <chr>              <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)       98.6       0.104    947.   0       
## 2 ChillsSweatsYes    0.410     0.115      3.58 0.000373

Model as box and whiskers plot

tidy(lm_fit) %>% 
dwplot(dot_args = list(size = 2, color = "black"),
         whisker_args = list(color = "black"),
         vline = geom_vline(xintercept = 0, colour = "grey50", linetype = 2))

# Model 2. Fitting a linear model to BodyTemp using all relevant predictors of interest If we remember from our EDA, the interesting predictors were

  • CoughIntensity (none/mild/moderate/severe)
  • ChillsSweats (y/n)
  • SubjectiveFever (y/n)

*Note, I am not using Pharyngitis because if did not offer an interesting relationship in both body temperature variable alone as well as fever variable.

# Using the tidymodels package, I am going to set up the linear model
# Set the engine
lm_mod <-  linear_reg() %>% 
  set_engine("lm") 
# Now I am fitting the model
lm_fit2 <- 
  lm_mod %>% 
  fit(BodyTemp ~ ChillsSweats * CoughIntensity * SubjectiveFever, data = processeddta)
tidy(lm_fit2)

Setting Predictions

# Setting what we want to predict, a fever
new_points <- expand.grid(BodyTemp = 100.4,
                          CoughIntensity = c("None","Mild", "Moderate", "Severe"))
new_points
##   BodyTemp CoughIntensity
## 1    100.4           None
## 2    100.4           Mild
## 3    100.4       Moderate
## 4    100.4         Severe

Set prediction for model 2

mean_pred <- predict(lm_fit2$fit, new_data = new_points)
#Set Confidence Interval
confint <- predict(lm_fit2$fit, 
                         new_data = new_points,
                         interval = 'confidence')

Model 3. Fitting a logistic model to Nausea using Headache the main predictor of interest

# Using the tidymodels package, I am going to set up the logistic model
# Set the engine
lm_mod1 <-  logistic_reg() %>% 
  set_engine("glm") 
# Now I am fitting the model
lm_fit3 <- 
  lm_mod1 %>% 
  fit(Nausea ~ Headache, data = processeddta)
tidy(lm_fit3)

Model 4. Fitting a logistic model to Nausea using all relevant predictors of interest

If we remember from our EDA, the interesting predictors were

  • Fatigue
  • ChillsSweats (y/n)
  • SubjectiveFever (y/n)
  • Pharyngitis
# Using the tidymodels package, I am going to set up the linear model
# Set the engine
lm_mod1 <-  logistic_reg() %>% 
  set_engine("glm") 
# Now I am fitting the model
lm_fit4 <- 
  lm_mod1 %>% 
  fit(Nausea ~ ChillsSweats * Fatigue * SubjectiveFever* Pharyngitis, data = processeddta)
tidy(lm_fit4)
